paragraphs.text:
%md
# Avoiding failed payments and involuntary churn

You have a hunch that weakening profits may be due to the company selling to non-optimal customers. This includes those customers who have good enough credit to purchase "big ticket items" like large televisions, appliances and durable goods on payment credit cards and payment plans but then fail to complete all their payments and have to return the purchased goods. The company takes a loss and has to resell the items at a discount as "used".

In your data assembled inside Oracle Autonomous Database, you have over 100 variables to consider to understand your data and to find hidden patterns and eventually build predictive models that target these "Good Credit" better customers. You want to first explore data using straightforward charts and graphs, but then move onto using Oracle Machine Learning's powerful in-database algorithms to automatically sift through the data to find patterns, identify new insights, and  make predictions that target the best customers--those who have both good enough credit and are able to complete all the payments.  

Let's take a look.

paragraphs.title: BUSINESS UNDERSTANDING
paragraphs.text:
%md
# Business Understanding

## Target "Good Credit" Customers Who Can Make All Payments and Don't Involuntary Churn

You want to avoid  customers who fail to make payments and  involuntarily churn.   You will be using Oracle Machine Learning's classification models in Autonomous Database. In the CREDIT_SCORING_100K dataset, you have tagged the disearable customers as "Good Credit" in the CREDIT_SCORING_100K table. Those who either have lower credit or have failed to keep up with their payments and have involuntarily churned you have labeled as "Other_Credit" customers. You want to build Oracle Machine Learning predictive models that target  "Good Credit" customer and can generate insights about them.  

Let's get started!

paragraphs.title: Bin customers by MAX_CC_SPENT_AMOUNT into 10 groups
paragraphs.text:
%sql

SELECT MAX_CC_SPENT_GROUP, COUNT(*) COUNT
FROM (SELECT MAX_CC_SPENT_AMOUNT, width_bucket(MAX_CC_SPENT_AMOUNT,
       100, 20000, 10) MAX_CC_SPENT_GROUP
       FROM CREDIT_SCORING_100K_V) 
GROUP BY MAX_CC_SPENT_GROUP
ORDER BY MAX_CC_SPENT_GROUP DESC;

# Data Preparation

To simplify, the data in this example has already been prepared to go directly to building machine learning models. The OML documentation covers in detail Automatic Data Preparation and related data preparation steps.  

See <https://docs.oracle.com/en/database/oracle/machine-learning/oml4sql/21/dmcon/machine-learning-basics.html#GUID-1F28AA79-0508-40C4-BB62-A7A7EAFE5E2F>

The following SQL creates a new column and recodes a numerical attribute into binned values. This can be done through a view as well. 

Data transformations like this are oftentimes helpful for capturing a specific aspect of a business problem like finding the "top customers".

RECODE a Target Variable

%script

ALTER TABLE ADMIN.CREDIT_SCORING_100K ADD(LIFETIME_VALUE_CATEGORY(VARCHAR2(100));
DELETE FROM ADMIN.CREDIT_SCORING_100K WHERE CUSTOMER_LIFETIME_VALUE IS NULL;
UPDATE CREDIT_SCORING_100K SET LIFETIME_VALUE_CATEGORY=CASE 
  WHEN CUSTOMER_LIFETIME_VALUE>=300000 THEN 'HIGH' 
  WHEN CUSTOMER_LIFETIME_VALUE>=100000 THEN 'MEDIUM' 
  ELSE 'LOW' END;
ALTER TABLE ADMIN.CREDIT_SCORING_100K DROP COLUMN CUSTOMER_LIFETIME_VALUE;

paragraphs.title: Apply model to new customers to make predictions about customers who are likely to be "Good Credit"
paragraphs.text:
%sql 

SELECT CUSTOMER_ID, CREDIT_SCORE_BIN, PREDICTION(N1_CLASS_MODEL_RF USING *) PREDICTION, ROUND(PREDICTION_PROBABILITY(N1_CLASS_MODEL_RF, NULL USING *)*100,2) PROB_CREDIT_SCORE_BIN 
FROM   CREDIT_SCORING_NEW_CUST_V
ORDER BY PROB_CREDIT_SCORE_BIN DESC

paragraphs.title: Create a new table CREDIT_SCORE_NEW_PREDICTIONS
paragraphs.text:
%script

BEGIN
  EXECUTE IMMEDIATE 'DROP TABLE CREDIT_SCORE_NEW_PREDICTIONS PURGE';
  EXCEPTION WHEN OTHERS THEN NULL; 
END;
/
-- create new table with model predictions and probabilities so we can view in other data visualization tools

CREATE TABLE CREDIT_SCORE_NEW_PREDICTIONS AS 
SELECT A.CUSTOMER_ID
	, A.PROB_GOOD_CREDIT
	, B.AGE, B.INCOME, B.TENURE, B.LOAN_TYPE, B.LOAN_AMOUNT, B.OCCUPATION, B.EDUCATION_LEVEL, B.MARITAL_STATUS
FROM (SELECT CUSTOMER_ID, round(PREDICTION_PROBABILITY(N1_CLASS_MODEL_RF, 'Good Credit' USING *),2) PROB_GOOD_CREDIT FROM CREDIT_SCORING_NEW_CUST_V) A
    , CREDIT_SCORING_100K_V B
WHERE A.CUSTOMER_ID = B.CUSTOMER_ID;

paragraphs.title: "What-if" real-time predictions on a single record
paragraphs.text:
%sql

-- Try "what-if" analysis to see real-time predictions by running this query, and then change WEALTH from 'Rich" to 'Poor" (in both parts of the query) 
--      and re-run to see lower probability of customer being a "Good Credit" customer. 
-- Hint: When the user specifies a subset of the predictors, OML will use the mean and mode values for the other predictors in the model.

SELECT PREDICTION(N1_CLASS_MODEL_RF USING 
                  'Rich' AS WEALTH, 5000 AS INCOME, 'Segment1' as CUSTOMER_DMG_SEGMENT, 'Gold' AS CUSTOMER_VALUE_SEGMENT, 30 AS AGE) PREDICTION,
       ROUND(PREDICTION_PROBABILITY(N1_CLASS_MODEL_RF, 'Good Credit' USING 
                  'Rich' AS WEALTH, 5000 AS INCOME, 'Segment1' as CUSTOMER_DMG_SEGMENT, 'Gold' AS CUSTOMER_VALUE_SEGMENT, 30 AS AGE)*100,1) LIKELY_PREDICTION_CORRECT_PCNT
FROM DUAL;
